"While, as Doody has shown, there were novels in the ancient world, these works were either not known or not regarded as novels by most early Americans. In the young Republic, both critics and advocates of fiction considered the novel a dis- tinctly modern genre. On ancient novels, see Doody 15-33.",
"For an account of the relationship between classical and modern republicanism in the Atlantic world of the late eighteenth and nineteenth century, see the intro- duction and chapters 1-2 of Gustafson, Imagining Deliberative Democracy.",
"Looby, introduction, and Waldstreicher. There is an extensive literature on the public sphere in the early Republic. On the relation between literary and po- litical public spheres in the early Republic, see Burgett 28-54, 87-90; and Dil- lon. Various critics have sought to qualify and supplement Warner's emphasis on print culture by emphasizing the role played by oratory in republican society. In addition to Looby, Voicing America, see Fliegelman and Gustafson, Eloquence Is Power. For a recent account that emphasizes the material conditions of the American public sphere, see Loughran 113-16.",
"Looby's call for attention to \"the deep, historical inextricability\" of literary read- ing and political participation explicitly invokes Habermas's structural account, but, I would suggest, it also implicitly points to important recent accounts of the early American literary public sphere, such as those of Burgett and Dillon, that Blochs account either overlooks or ignores.",
"Dillon has shown how the public-private divide in the print public sphere is a false (ideological) one: the private is always a back projection from the public and even texts coded as private remain important public objects (25-48). Yet this ideological distinction was a powerful historically operative force that shaped both the writing and reception of fiction in the early Republic.",
"See, for example, Habermas 28.",
"It should be noted that not all accounts of the early American public sphere rely on Habermas's structural division between literary and political public spheres: Warner's foundational Letters of the Republic, for example, persuasively shows how a unified set of discourse norms and conventions govern republican print culture, including the novel. Habermas's structural division, however, does help to capture the transatlantic negotiation in which early American fiction was in- volved: for even as Americans wrote fiction oriented toward republican, political frameworks of value, they drew on the novels written in England, where there was a more fully differentiated framework of literary value and a discrete literary public sphere.",
"See especially Davidson 233-66 and Looby, Voicing America 203-306.",
"See also White.",
"Kelleher has carefully charted Brackenridge's multiplicity of justifications for the work that warns us against attempting to generalize about the text's project: \"On twenty-two of these occasions he confesses a serious moral intention. Signifi- cantly less often he denies in a mock-serious tone that the book is a satire (five times); calls it an exercise in style only (seven times), a burlesque (once), an adventures narrative (four times), pure nonsense (five times), a playful satire (once), and history-memoir-biography (eight times)\" (56).",
"Even if we limit ourselves to the early United States—and there were certainly politically engaged fictions written on both sides of the Atlantic—this strand of politically oriented fiction includes works by Royall Tyler, Charles Brock- den Brown, Leonora Sansay, Lydia Maria Child, and James Fenimore Cooper (among others). On \"the sustained treatment of modern republicanism\" and its political procedures in the works of Child and Cooper, see Gustafson, Imagining Deliberative Democracy 152-91.",
"T. Martin's influential account of early America's antifictional culture links this epistemological suspicion in early American antifiction to the influence of Scot- tish Common Sense philosophy in the early Republic.",
"For an account of Brackenridge's vexed relation to literature and his understand- ing of its position in his career, see Ferguson 119-23.",
"Elliott has argued that \"the story of the narrator-artist-hero emerges as the most important\" narrative in the story (184). For accounts that explore Brackenridge's conception of authorship, see Watts 28-29 and Rice 129-41. On authority in the novel, see Patterson 34-61.",
"In writing on \"risk culture\" in early America, Fichtelberg argues that the values we now associate with the public sphere—trust, rituals of oath taking, ideals of authority and honor—were \"cast in doubt\" in early America, leaving writers grasping for \"response[s] to this uncertainty\" (8). In staging the career risk he undertakes in publishing his political satire, Brackenridge provides an especially explicit instance of what Fichtelberg refers to as a \"performative response\" to this problem: he uses this personal risk as a means of establishing his honorable and disinterested—as opposed to self-serving—intentions in publication. That is, Brackenridge draws attention to the risk he undergoes in order to establish his text's authority and reliability in a public sphere rife with uncertainty.",
"For an account of Brackenridge's role in these affairs, see Newlin 87-107,134-76.",
"Brackenridge's career demonstrates that he was not above newspaper satire: he both wrote and published referential periodical satires. Brackenridge's occa- sional embrace of referential satire, however, suggests the need to take seriously his claims that Modern Chivalry is doing something different. On Brackenridge's newspaper career, see Newlin 44-58.",
"On the rise of political parties in this era, see Chambers. On the rise of the parti- san press during this period, including the careers of Cobbett and Callender, see Pasley. On how the increasingly vitriolic and divisive political rhetoric shaped the novel in this period, see Davidson 233-48. On the ideological crisis for re- publicanism, the contestation over its meaning, and anxieties about American interest and corruption, see G. Wood.",
"This is not to suggest that Brackenridge was above either partisan politics or the emerging party press. He simultaneously participated in it and critiqued it: as Pasley puts it, Brackenridge's \"attitudes are revealing of the Republican gentry's contradictory attitude toward their own press\" (156). His ambivalence reflects his simultaneous dedication to the ideals of classical republicanism and his engage- ment in the political struggles of his moment.",
"Both Watts and S. Wood have demonstrated how Brackenridge shows how \"the language of paternal authority\" is revealed to serve the interests of a duplici- tous elite (Watts 38). See Watts 38 and Wood 94. Elliott has charted the unstable relation of both the narrator and Brackenridge to Farrago across the volumes (182-91). Jordan argues that Brackenridge endorses this deceptive reasoning as a way of defending the social order (67-71). While Lukasik emphasizes how for Brackenridge \"dissimulation... poses a particular problem for democratic poli- tics,\" he also contends that Modern Chivalry does not critique Farrago's lack of disinterest, but is suggesting that his appeal to disinterest is archaic (143, 150). Nelson also takes up the question of reason's status in the novel, arguing \"the novel expounds reasonability against rationality\" (32).",
"There has been extensive treatment of Brackenridge's republicanism (or anti- republicanism). Much of it focuses on whether Brackenridge's deployment of the truisms of republicanism—voiced by both Farrago and the narrator—are earnest, ironic, nostalgic, or a complex mix. For competing accounts of Bracken- ridge's relation to republicanism, see Looby, Voicing America 243-49; Engell; W. Martin; P. Gilmore; Jordan 58-77; M. Gilmore.",
"On Brackenridge's engagement with print culture, see Rice, who argues Bracken- ridge \"feared the power of a democratic print culture... to consolidate a coercive public opinion and was anxious that such a consensus would stifle the critical individualism that made a liberal republic philosophically if not practically pos- sible\" (127). Rice asserts that Brackenridge's text seeks to \"demystify the claims for... textual authority.\" While Rice sees Brackenridge as turning to \"prose fic- tion\" to critique the textual authority of print, he gives no attention to the fiction - ality of fiction, focusing it as part of a broader endorsement of belles lettres (133).",
"For an account of this affair, see Newlin 241-50.",
"As the volumes progress and fictionality is increasingly valued for its lack of re- lation to actual persons and by extension its disinterest, the disavowals of refer- ence to Findley in volume 1 seem progressively disingenuous because these rep- resentations do seem to be motivated by personal political struggle. But they also stand out as singular within the growing totality of Modern Chivalry for this reason.",
"On Brown's use of fictionality, see my essay \"Whatever May Be the Merit.\"",
